EXAMINING THE CHALLENGES AND OPPORTUNITIES IN THE IMPLEMENTATION OF NATIONAL DISASTER PLANNING POLICIES AT THE MUNICIPAL LEVEL: A CASE STUDY OF NANUMBA NORTH MUNICIPAL ASSEMBLY IN THE NORTHERN REGION OF GHANA

Laurens

November 28, 2025

Abstract

This report presents

1 QUALITATIVE ANALYSIS

2 Data familiarisation-concise summary (what participants discussed)

Participants across the NADMO FGD, Planning Unit FGD, environmental health and fire service KIIs, and chiefs/assembly members repeatedly described the same core reality: Nanumba North faces frequent windstorms, bushfires and flooding, and local responses are hampered more by resource, logistics, institutional and governance problems than by lack of local will. key achievements (re-roofing after Chamba fire; some school repairs) are noted, but participants emphasised that responses are ad hoc and often ineffective because NADMO and other agencies lack vehicles, equipment, stocked relief stores, functional hydrants, timely funds, and decentralised authority. Coordination between some agencies (e.g., NADMOfire servicehospital) works pragmatically at times, but the Assemblys treatment of memos, funding delays and perceived politicisation of relief undermine trust. Community interviewees stress poor follow-up after assessments, limited training and weak partnerships; local strengths are social solidarity, local knowledge and occasional volunteer efforts. Opportunities identified include: strengthened sensitisation (radio/TV); stocking municipal relief stores; decentralising authority and funds; empowering physical planning to improve access; tree planting and afforestation; and targeted modest investments in mobility (vehicles) and logistics.

Main patterns/ideas:

  • Material/operational constraints dominate (vehicles, life jackets, PPE, chainsaws, fire engine, hydrants, stocked stores).

  • Financial bottlenecks and delayed/insufficient funds (national and common fund releases).

  • Capacity issues - numbers and training (mixed perceptions across units).

  • Coordination is uneven-functional with some partners (fire, hospital) but constrained by assembly bureaucracy and weak inclusion of some services.

  • Politics & trust-contested: some say politics affects distribution; others deny political interference at prevention stage.

  • Community engagement & behaviour-knowledge exists but attitudes, livelihoods (charcoal, firewood) and cultural practices (e.g., burning for grazing) create risk.

  • Practical opportunities: decentralisation, pre-stocked relief, sensitisation campaigns, tree planting, empowering planning for accessibility.

5 D. Interpretation & discussion

(what each theme means in relation to research problem, relevant theory, and policy/practice implications)

Only based on participants words.

5.1 Theme 1-Operational resource constraints that limit implementation

Relation to objectives: Directly answers Objective 1 (financial, logistical barriers). The transcripts show that logistics (transport, equipment, stocked stores, hydrants) are the most immediate, repeated barrier to translating policy into action at municipal level. NADMO staff and GNFS indicate that even routine prevention (sensitisation, community visits) is curtailed by lack of vehicles and PPE.

Theoretical connection: Institutional capacity frameworks distinguish hardware (equipment, infrastructure) from software (rules, skills). Here hardware deficits clearly block policy implementation.

Implications: Policy must prioritise tangible, locally appropriate logistics (municipal vehicles, lifejackets, chainsaws, functional hydrants and fire engines, and local stockpiles). Without these, top-level policies remain rhetorical.

5.2 Theme 2-Financial bottlenecks and bureaucratic delays

Relation to objectives: Addresses Objective 1 and Objective 4. Participants report allocated funds are either delayed or not released; national and common funds are irregular and insufficient. This undermines timely disaster prevention/response.

Theoretical connection: Fiscal decentralisation literature highlights that timely, predictable funding is necessary for local governance to act. The transcripts call for ring-fenced or decentralised allocations.

Implications: Recommendations should include establishing predictable, ring-fenced disaster funds at MMDA level, faster release mechanisms, and financial accountability measures to reconcile speed and transparency.

5.3 Theme 3-Uneven institutional capacity and coordination

Relation to objectives: Directly addresses Objective 2 (institutional capacity). While some cross-agency relations (NADMOfirehospital) are functional, municipal bureaucracy (treatment of memos; need for clearance from national) and centralised training undermine localization of policy. Staff numbers are improving but training, office space and equipment still limit capacity.

Theoretical connection: Governance frameworks emphasise that coordination requires clear mandates, local autonomy, and routine joint exercises. The data show joint drills and local contingency planning are weak or absent (e.g., GNFS no joint drills with NADMO).

Implications: Policy should enable more local autonomy for contingency actions, regular joint drills, decentralised and frequent training, and simple SOPs that empower local units to act within national policy.

5.4 Theme 4-Politics, trust and community perceptions

Relation to objectives: Speaks to Objective 1 (political barriers) and Objective 3 (opportunities to strengthen implementation). Perceptions of politicisation in relief distribution and visible follow-up failures generate community mistrust, sometimes hostility toward staff.

Theoretical connection: Disaster governance research highlights the risk that perceived unfair distribution erodes social trust and reduces reporting-exactly what chiefs and NADMO officers report.

Implications: Operational transparency (clear beneficiary criteria, public inventories of stocked relief, community complaint mechanisms) and insulated, ring-fenced local response budgets can reduce perceptions of politicisation.

5.5 Theme 5-Community strengths and prevention opportunities

Relation to objectives: Aligns with Objective 3 and Objective 4 (opportunities and recommendations). Communities display social capital and local knowledge; participants propose practical, affordable preventive measures (sensitisation via radio, tree planting, improve building layout, reservoir construction).

Theoretical connection: Community-based disaster risk reduction approaches emphasise leveraging local knowledge and low-cost prevention (awareness, natural buffers) as highly effective complements to formal systems.

Implications: Investments that pair modest logistics (driver + motorbike/vehicle) with intensified sensitisation and community engagement can yield high prevention dividends. Empowering planning to ensure access and promoting nature-based measures are low-cost opportunities.

6 E. Additional notes on contradictions / unclear points (explicit)

Staffing adequacy is contested. NADMO and Planning Unit members both claim increased staff numbers (11 24; GNFS 42) yet planning officers and other KIs argue numbers are still insufficient given the municipal size. This suggests a relative perception gap: absolute numbers rose but may still not match geographic demands.

Political influence views diverge. NADMO NO1 denies political interference in prevention; others (NO2, NO3; chiefs) report politicisation in relief allocation. This divergence may reflect different vantage points (internal staff vs community perceptions) or sensitivity to acknowledging political influence.

Training frequency unclear. Some say training occurs annually or every few years at regional level; others say training is insufficient. The transcripts lack specifics on training content, duration, or participation metrics.

7 F. Thematic map (textual description)

At the centre: Policy implementation at municipal level-surrounded by three immediate, mutually reinforcing constraints: (1) Operational resources (vehicles, equipment, stocked stores, hydrants), (2) Finance & bureaucracy (delays, non-release, need for national clearance), and (3) Institutional capacity & coordination (training, joint drills, assembly bottlenecks). These constraints produce community distrust and perceived politicisation, which in turn reduces reporting and cooperation. Opposing these constraints are community strengths and low-cost prevention options (sensitisation, tree planting, planning), representing practical leverage points. Arrows: resources finance (lack of funds causes no resources); bureaucracy slow response community distrust; community strengths potential to amplify prevention if logistics & funds enable action.

8 G. Narrative write-up of findings

Municipal actors in Nanumba North report a sobering mismatch between national disaster policy intent and local operational reality. Across NADMO staff, the planning unit, the fire service, environmental health officials, and traditional leaders, the clearest and most frequently cited constraint is material and logistical scarcity: the municipal NADMO office lacks vehicles, lifejackets, personal protective equipment and pre-positioned relief stocks; the fire service operates with a single engine across multiple districts and only one functional hydrant. These deficits have direct, measurable consequencescommunity sensitisation campaigns fail to reach remote electoral areas, flood-prone communities remain inaccessible during emergencies, and staff safety is compromised during water rescues.

Compounding material shortages are financial and bureaucratic bottlenecks. Participants described funds that are either late, insufficient, or require protracted memos and national clearance before disbursement. The resulting pattern is that local teams often undertake assessment and reporting but cannot deliver timely assistance; this gap erodes community trust, fuels perceptions of politicised relief distribution, and sometimes places field officers at risk of public hostility. Several interviewees recommended ring-fenced municipal allocations or clearer, faster release protocols so that local units can act within the window where prevention or mitigation is meaningful.

Institutional capacity and coordination present a mixed picture. On the positive side, NADMO collaborates with the fire service and hospital on specific tasks, and environmental health inputs are captured into municipal planning instruments like MESSAP and the MMTDP. However, crucial weaknesses remaintraining for staff is irregular and centralised at the regional level, joint drills and contingency exercises are largely absent, and assembly processes (how memos are treated) repeatedly block nimble action. These institutional gaps limit the municipal assemblys ability to convert national disaster guidance into standard operating procedures at the local level.

Despite these constraints, there are tangible opportunities for improvement grounded in local realities. Community social capitalcollective responses to fires, local knowledge of landscapes, and openness of chiefs to engagementoffers a foundation for community-based DRR (disaster risk reduction). Participants proposed immediately actionable and low-cost measures: intensifying radio/TV sensitisation, pre-stocking relief stores, modest investments in mobility (a pickup or additional motorbikes), empowering the physical planning unit to improve access for emergency services, and nature-based prevention such as tree-planting campaigns. Together, these measures could substantially increase preparedness and provide visible, quick wins that rebuild trust while higher-cost investments (hydrants, fire engines) are pursued.

9 H. Key insights and concrete, context-specific recommendations

Below are prioritised, realistic recommendations tailored to Nanumba North Municipal Assembly (ranked by short/medium/long term and cost-sensitivity).

9.1 Short term (low cost; high impact)

  1. Ring-fence a modest Rapid Response fund at MMDA level-establish a small, locally controlled contingency pot (managed by NADMO with transparent ledger and receipts) to enable same-day procurement or transport for immediate needs (e.g., fuel, small relief items). Rationale: addresses funding delay problem and reduces assessment-only responses.

  2. Pre-position essential relief kits in municipal stores-restore minimal stockpiles of non-perishables, roofing sheets, blankets, life jackets and PPE with clear inventory publicly displayed. Rationale: reduces lead time and builds community trust.

  3. Dedicate one or two motorbikes and one pickup to NADMO operational/sensitisation teams-even one reliable vehicle plus motorbikes dramatically improves reach across 43 electoral areas. Rationale: directly tackles mobility barrier.

  4. Expand radio/TV sensitisation calendar before high-risk seasons (harmattan/wet season) and publish schedule. Rationale: low cost, leverages existing platforms and community reach.

9.2 Medium term (moderate cost)

  1. Create standard operating procedures (SOPs) for rapid municipal action that allow NADMO to act under predefined thresholds without waiting for national clearance (within clearly defined financial limits and transparency measures). Rationale: streamlines bureaucracy while preserving oversight.

  2. Regular, decentralised training & joint drills-monthly or quarterly inter-agency tabletop exercises and annual field drills with GNFS, NADMO, EH, health and community volunteers. Rationale: builds coordination, clarifies roles and reduces duplication.

  3. Establish transparent beneficiary selection and complaint mechanism for relief distribution (public lists, community verification). Rationale: reduces perceptions of politicisation and increases legitimacy.

  4. Empower physical planning unit for emergency access-require building setbacks, designated access lanes and enforcement for high-risk zones; pilot quick mapping of high-risk communities. Rationale: improves fire-service accessibility.

9.3 Long term (capital investment; structural)

  1. Invest in functional fire hydrants & additional fire engine at strategic location (seek regional/national or donor funding). Rationale: essential to effective firefighting in urban/peri-urban areas.

  2. Advocate for policy decentralisation of certain disaster funds and procurement authority to MMDAs (through regional/national advocacy), with performance and accountability metrics. Rationale: structural fix to funding delays.

  3. Promote livelihood-sensitive prevention programs (sustainable charcoal production, alternative livelihoods, afforestation incentives) in partnership with agricultural/NGO programs. Rationale: addresses root causes of bushfire risk.

10 I. Note something small here

Limitations: note that perceptions on politicisation and staffing adequacy are contested; indicate where additional quantitative budgeting or service-coverage data could verify claims (e.g., transport assets inventory, timeliness of fund disbursement records).
